Chapter 5
Psychological Counselling
5.1 Details on data processing in the context of psychological counselling
5.1.1 Purposes and legal bases of data processing
5.1.2 Categories of data processed
5.1.3 Sources of data and obligation to provide them
5.1.4 Internal recipients of the data
5.1.5 External recipients of the data
5.1.6 Storage period of the data
5.2 Third-party tools
5.2.1 Salesforce CRM
5.2.2 Google Cloud Platform
5.2.3 Retarus GmbH
5.2.4 HubSpot
In the context of psychological counselling provided by psychological or medical psychotherapists (hereinafter referred to as counsellors), data about the person to be counseled (hereinafter referred to as client) as well as the data necessary for the counselling are processed.
In order to provide psychological counselling, we collect and process both general, personal data of the clients and counsellors as well as data relating to the content of the counselling.
Important note: A storage or recording of the video calls explicitly does not take place without prior, separate consent.
5.1 Details on data processing in the context of psychological counselling
5.1.1 Purposes and legal bases of data processing
MindDoc Health and MindDoc Healthcare may only process client data if this is required or permitted by law or if the client has given his/her consent.
MindDoc Health and MindDoc Healthcare process client data within the framework of psychological counselling for the purposes listed below:
Organisation and implementation of the counselling activity
We process personal data to the extent necessary to provide counselling services to clients and to ensure the best possible psychological counselling.
  This includes processing for counselling reasons (e.g. via appointment documentation, work materials), to make and remind appointments, for authentication
  and billing vis-à-vis the employer, for reasons of controlling or auditing, to support and maintain the technical systems and applications used for counselling,
  and to fix technical errors or other questions from the client.
This data processing is carried out on the legal basis of Article 6 Paragraph 1 Page 1 b) DSGVO (contract performance) in connection with the terms of use,
  which regulate the counselling activities vis-à-vis the clients.
Insofar as special categories of personal data, including in particular health data, are processed within the scope of the counselling activities,
  this is done in accordance with the regulation in Article 9 Paragraph 2 h) of the GDPR.
Performance measurement and quality assurance
If clients consent in advance, we process personal data, including health data, to measure the effectiveness of the counselling, for internal
  quality assurance and analysis purposes, to improve counselling processes and content, to improve the user experience during counselling, and to measure
  the stability of the counselling service. Among other things, we use standardised questionnaires for this purpose.
This data processing is carried out on the legal basis of Article 6, Paragraph 1, Page  1 a), Article 9, Paragraph 2 a) DSGVO in conjunction with
  the consent given.
Evaluations for the employer without personal data
In order to be able to provide employers of clients with reports on the use and success evaluations of the counselling services provided,
  we process personal data in order to produce these reports. The reports do not contain any personal data.
This data processing is carried out on the legal basis of Article 6, Paragraph 1, Page 1 f) DSGVO (legitimate interests) and in the interest of
  MindDoc Health and MindDoc Healthcare in providing employers with a reporting option on the counselling services provided,
  as well as in the interest of the respective employer in being able to check the success of the counselling service provided for its employees.
5.1.2 Categories of data processed
The following categories of personal data may be processed by MindDoc Health and MindDoc Healthcare for the purposes listed above within the scope of the psychological counselling:
Data processed by clients:
First name(s)
Surname(s)
Title (e.g. Dr., Prof.)
E-mail address
Date of birth
Telephone number
Postal address
Company name
Gender
IP address
Profile photo
Appointment request
Voucher code
As well as details of booked psychological counselling appointments:
Date/time (start, end)
Reasons for cancellations and/or postponements
Timing of appointment cancellations for the charging of a cancellation fee
The following data of clients, which may include information on physical or mental health ("health data"), may be processed in the context of counselling:
Reason for counselling (i.e. reason for visit such as conflict resolution, relationship problems, decision-making, crises, discrimination, overwork,
dealing with stress and excessive demands, fears, work-life balance, dealing with illness, death or grief, general dissatisfaction, dealing with change,
loneliness or isolation).
Qualitative answers and notes entered in writing in practice lessons, questionnaires or within the electronic chat (e.g. answers about thoughts and feelings).
Quantitative values from questionnaires
Date, time, duration and nature of activities between client and counsellor or service and support team.
Interview documentation contents by the counsellor
5.1.3 Sources of data and obligation to provide them
The data listed above is either collected from the clients themselves or automatically stored by the counsellors or the system.
Insofar as data is collected from the clients themselves and it is indicated that these are mandatory fields, their provision is contractually
necessary in order to be able to provide the counselling services.
5.1.4 Internal recipients of the data
The counsellors involved in psychological counselling have access to client data. The counsellors are either subject to professional secrecy or a duty of confidentiality.
If necessary for administrative purposes, an administrative employee (e.g. administration, technical support) can also access personal client data.
The confidential handling of your data is also guaranteed here by corresponding confidentiality obligations.
5.1.5 External recipients of the data
In addition to the internal recipients of MindDoc Health and MindDoc Healthcare, we use external
data processors (so-called order processors) for data processing for the purposes listed above, which we have commissioned taking into account the obligations
arising from Article 28 DS-GVO. We oblige such service providers to comply with legal standards with regard to data protection and data security.
As a result, the processors are bound by our instructions and are regularly monitored by us. Within the following categories, we use such processors in accordance
with Article 28 DS-GVO, which are necessary for the development and provision of the online counselling and related services: Hosting of data
and applications (e.g. Google Cloud Hosting), email dispatch, customer support, accounting. For more details on third-party providers we use,
please see the
"Third-party tools"
section below.
5.1.6 Storage period of the data
MindDoc Healthcare stores the personal data as well as the documentation on your psychological counselling for a period of 3 years,
unless longer statutory retention obligations apply (e.g. 6 years according to the German Commercial Code).
